---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Our Story &mdash; Red Fox Inn | Lancaster, NH"
  description="Named for Lancaster&rsquo;s bronze fox, sculpted by Anna Hyatt Huntington in 1913. The story of the fox, the forest, the town, and the inn."
  transparentHeader
>
  <main id="main-content">

    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="relative bg-fox-brown text-snow px-6 py-40 md:py-56 overflow-hidden -mt-[88px] pt-[160px] md:pt-[200px]">
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-br from-night via-fox-brown to-deep-red/60"></div>
      <div class="relative z-10 max-w-4xl mx-auto text-center">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.4em] text-fox-orange mb-10 font-medium">
          Our Story
        </p>
        <h1 class="font-display font-light text-5xl md:text-7xl lg:text-[5.5rem] leading-[1.05] mb-12 text-snow">
          A New Chapter<br />on an Old Road.
        </h1>
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-xl md:text-2xl text-fox-cream leading-[1.5] max-w-3xl mx-auto">
          Red Fox Inn sits at 112 Main Street in Lancaster, New Hampshire &mdash; the county seat of Co&ouml;s County, the gateway to the Great North Woods, and a place where every view out the window exists because one local boy thought big.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Section 1: The Fox -->
    <section class="bg-fox-cream px-6 py-24 md:py-32">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          01 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Fox
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          Lancaster&rsquo;s fox<br />is a bronze one.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body font-light text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] space-y-6">
          <p>
            The red fox isn&rsquo;t just our name &mdash; it&rsquo;s Lancaster&rsquo;s official town symbol. In 1913, when Lancaster celebrated its sesquicentennial, the town commissioned sculptor <em class="font-display">Anna Vaughn Hyatt Huntington</em> to cast a fox in bronze. Huntington was no local artisan &mdash; her <em class="font-display">Joan of Arc</em> stands in Riverside Park in Manhattan, her <em class="font-display">El Cid</em> guards the entrance to the Hispanic Society of America. The bronze fox she created for Lancaster still sits in Centennial Park, three blocks from our front door.
          </p>
          <p>
            The town chose the fox for what it represents: clever, caring, independent, and at home with the wild. We chose the name Red Fox Inn because no other words capture this place better.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto mt-20 md:mt-24 px-6 text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-fox-red text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.2]">
          &ldquo;Clever, caring, independent,<br />and at home with the wild.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-warm-gray mt-8 font-medium">
          &mdash; The Town of Lancaster, on its fox
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Section 2: The Forest -->
    <section class="bg-snow px-6 py-24 md:py-32">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          02 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Forest
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          A Lancaster kid<br />saved the mountains.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body font-light text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] space-y-6">
          <p>
            Every mountain you see from Lancaster exists as protected land because of a boy who grew up on one of them. <em class="font-display">John Wingate Weeks</em> was born and raised here, went on to become a U.S. Senator and Secretary of War, and authored the Weeks Act &mdash; signed by President Taft on March 1, 1911. That single law created the White Mountain National Forest and 47 other eastern national forests, protecting over 20 million acres.
          </p>
          <p>
            Weeks&rsquo;s summer lodge &mdash; a 1912 fieldstone mansion with a 56-foot observation tower &mdash; is now Weeks State Park, a five-minute drive from the inn.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto mt-20 md:mt-24 px-6 text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-forest-green text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.2]">
          &ldquo;A Lancaster kid looked at these mountains<br />and decided they should belong to everyone.&rdquo;
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-20 md:mt-24">
        <p class="font-body font-light text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75]">
          Stand at the top of that tower and you&rsquo;ll see the legacy of a Lancaster kid who thought big.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Section 3: The Town -->
    <section class="bg-fox-cream px-6 py-24 md:py-32">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          03 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Town
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          Chartered in 1763.<br />Stubborn ever since.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body font-light text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] space-y-6">
          <p>
            Lancaster was chartered on July 6, 1763. The first settlers arrived the following spring with twenty head of cattle and twelve acres of corn seed &mdash; only to watch a freak August frost destroy the entire crop. They stayed anyway. That stubbornness runs deep here.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Israel River that flows through downtown was called <em class="font-display">Siwooganock</em> &mdash; &ldquo;place of the burnt pine trees&rdquo; &mdash; by the Abenaki. Co&ouml;s County itself takes its name from the Abenaki word for &ldquo;white pines,&rdquo; and remains the only place name in America officially spelled with a diaeresis.
          </p>
          <p>
            Next door to the inn, St. Paul&rsquo;s Episcopal Church &mdash; built in 1876 and modeled after a small English country church &mdash; is described by the Library of Congress as one of the most photographed churches in New England. The Lancaster Fair has run every year since 1870.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto mt-20 md:mt-24 px-6 text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-fox-red text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.2]">
          &ldquo;The friendly town<br />in the friendly state.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-warm-gray mt-8 font-medium">
          &mdash; Lancaster&rsquo;s town motto
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Section 4: The Colonel -->
    <section class="bg-snow px-6 py-24 md:py-32">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          04 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Colonel
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          One last battle.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body font-light text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] space-y-6">
          <p>
            <em class="font-display">Colonel Edward E. Cross</em> set type at the <em class="font-display">Co&ouml;s Democrat</em> newspaper in Lancaster as a fifteen-year-old, then went on to found Arizona&rsquo;s first newspaper, command the Fifth New Hampshire &mdash; the Union regiment that suffered the highest infantry casualties of the Civil War &mdash; and was killed at Gettysburg on July 3, 1863. His grave is a short walk from the inn.
          </p>
          <p>
            When General Hancock told him that morning, <em>&ldquo;Colonel Cross, this day will bring you a star,&rdquo;</em> Cross replied:
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto mt-16 md:mt-20 px-6 text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-fox-red text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl leading-[1.2]">
          &ldquo;No, General.<br />This is my last battle.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-warm-gray mt-8 font-medium">
          &mdash; Col. Edward E. Cross, July 3, 1863
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-16 md:mt-20">
        <p class="font-body font-light text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75]">
          He was right.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Section 5: The Inn -->
    <section class="bg-fox-cream px-6 py-24 md:py-32">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          05 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; The Inn
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          A 1950s motor lodge,<br />still earning its keep.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body font-light text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] space-y-6">
          <p>
            Red Fox Inn is a 27-room motor lodge at the center of downtown Lancaster. We&rsquo;re operated by <em class="font-display">Hanuram, LLC</em>, and we&rsquo;re part of a family of North Country properties that includes Eastgate Inn in Littleton and Saffron Inn in Auburn, Maine. We&rsquo;ve been in the hospitality business in this region for over eight years.
          </p>
          <p>
            The building dates to the 1950s, and we honor that heritage &mdash; the exterior-corridor format means you park at your door, whether you&rsquo;re arriving by car, motorcycle, ATV, or snowmobile. We&rsquo;ve upgraded every room with new mattresses, laminate wood floors, flat-screen TVs, fiber-optic Wi-Fi, and modern furniture, while keeping the retro character that makes a motor lodge worth staying at.
          </p>
          <p>
            We&rsquo;re not a luxury resort and we don&rsquo;t pretend to be. We&rsquo;re a warm, clean, well-run inn in one of the most beautiful small towns in America &mdash; run by people who live here and love it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Section 6: Since 1955 -->
    <section class="bg-snow px-6 py-24 md:py-32">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-fox-red mb-6 font-medium">
          06 &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Since 1955
        </p>
        <h2 class="font-display font-light text-4xl md:text-6xl leading-[1.1] mb-12">
          The same patch<br />of Main Street.
        </h2>
        <div class="font-body font-light text-lg md:text-xl text-fox-brown leading-[1.75] space-y-6">
          <p>
            The Lancaster Motel opened its doors in 1955 and quickly became a landmark on Routes 2 and 3 in downtown Lancaster. These vintage postcards show the property in its early days &mdash; the distinctive curved entrance and the classic motor court layout that welcomed travelers to the North Country for decades. Red Fox Inn carries that tradition forward.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto mt-16 md:mt-20 px-6">
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 md:gap-8">
          <figure class="bg-fox-cream p-3 md:p-4 shadow-sm">
            <div class="aspect-[4/3] overflow-hidden bg-fox-brown">
              <img
                src="/images/heritage/vintage-postcard-1.webp"
                alt="Vintage postcard of The Lancaster Motel from the 1950s &mdash; the original property at 112 Main Street with curved entrance and motor court layout"
                width="861"
                height="545"
                loading="lazy"
                decoding="async"
                class="w-full h-full object-cover"
              />
            </div>
            <figcaption class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-warm-gray mt-3 font-medium text-center">
              Postcard &middot; circa 1955
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="bg-fox-cream p-3 md:p-4 shadow-sm">
            <div class="aspect-[4/3] overflow-hidden bg-fox-brown">
              <img
                src="/images/heritage/vintage-postcard-2.webp"
                alt="Vintage postcard of The Lancaster Motel &mdash; close-up of the property and signage in mid-century motor lodge style"
                width="1200"
                height="814"
                loading="lazy"
                decoding="async"
                class="w-full h-full object-cover"
              />
            </div>
            <figcaption class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-warm-gray mt-3 font-medium text-center">
              Postcard &middot; mid-century
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="bg-fox-cream p-3 md:p-4 shadow-sm">
            <div class="aspect-[4/3] overflow-hidden bg-fox-brown">
              <img
                src="/images/property/exterior-front-2-1600.webp"
                srcset="/images/property/exterior-front-2-800.webp 800w, /images/property/exterior-front-2-1600.webp 1400w"
                sizes="(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 33vw"
                alt="The same curved-roof 1955 building today &mdash; exterior of the property in downtown Lancaster, New Hampshire"
                width="1400"
                height="1050"
                loading="lazy"
                decoding="async"
                class="w-full h-full object-cover"
              />
            </div>
            <figcaption class="font-body text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-warm-gray mt-3 font-medium text-center">
              The same curved roof &middot; today
            </figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>


    <!-- Closing pull quote -->
    <section class="relative bg-fox-brown text-snow px-6 py-40 md:py-56 overflow-hidden">
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-br from-night via-fox-brown to-deep-red/60"></div>
      <div class="relative z-10 max-w-5xl mx-auto text-center">
        <p class="font-display font-light italic text-fox-amber text-4xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl leading-[1.15]">
          &ldquo;Where the North Woods<br />welcome you home.&rdquo;
        </p>
        <div class="mt-16">
          <a
            href="/stay/"
            class="font-body inline-block px-10 py-4 bg-fox-red text-snow text-sm font-medium tracking-[0.15em] uppercase hover:bg-deep-red transition-colors"
          >
            Plan a Visit
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
</BaseLayout>
